---
Assassins are stealth-based melee combatants whose tradition descends from imperial intelligence agents trained in what their original administrative framework called "political obstacle removal." No founding guild exists. The tradition transmits through handler-operative chains — a senior practitioner trains one or very few junior practitioners, and those operatives eventually become handlers themselves. This structure produces no institutional footprint that external actors can identify and suppress, while allowing chains to exchange knowledge through referral relationships without formal organization. The tradition's philosophy, which distinguishes it from common hired killers, is the "perfect kill" doctrine: minimum disruption necessary to achieve the intended outcome, where disruption includes unnecessary casualties, political blowback, and improvised violence that degrades the practitioner's situational awareness. Study of targets and environments before engagement is treated as the minimum necessary preparation rather than excessive caution. The tradition maintains referral relationships with institutional actors across all five cities — informal social infrastructure maintained through reliable delivery and discreet handling. Practitioners who reveal which institutional actors have used the referral chain exit it permanently. Kiess's anti-sealed-warrant charter produces more assassinations per capita than other cities not from greater violence but because the legal framework attracts practitioners who need reliable non-institutional operating contexts. The Nightblade adept path synthesizes Assassin tradition positioning-and-patience methodology with Warlock shadow-compact practice.

