Khenari sacred record doctrine holds that death must be correctly documented — the passage of a person from living to dead requires specific rites that create the spiritual record enabling proper judgment. Assassination victims frequently lack these rites because the nature of the death is concealed or the location is unknown. Khenari clerics in Midgaard have developed a forensic rite practice for documenting deaths where the circumstances are unclear — a practice that intersects uncomfortably with Guard Command homicide investigation when the forensic rite produces documentation that implies a death was not what official records claim. The Sealed Names Apparatus has classified several forensic rite records under sealed warrant. Khenari clerics in Midgaard's temple districts maintain their own parallel archive of forensic rite documentation that has not been transferred to the Apparatus, on the grounds that spiritual records are outside civic registry jurisdiction.

flags KIESS ASHBORN
---
Ashborn forge-culture treats direct action as the appropriate response to identified threats: if something needs doing, you do it with your own hands, you document what you did, and you stand behind the result. The Assassin tradition's defining characteristics — indirection, deniability, concealed identity — are in fundamental tension with Ashborn direct-action values. Ashborn practitioners who have entered the Assassin tradition have typically done so from a practical rather than philosophical standpoint: the frontier context of Kiess creates situations where identified threats cannot be addressed through direct action without triggering consequences that harm the community, and deniable elimination is the operationally correct choice even if it is culturally alien. Ashborn Wall Command auxiliaries who develop Assassin tradition skills through frontier intelligence work exist in a social position that requires careful management within Ashborn community contexts.

