Ushabti legal doctrine holds that every significant action produces claims that persist and require eventual adjudication. Assassination is, in Ushabti framing, a claim made against a specific person — the claim that their continued existence is incompatible with some other interest — and the outcome of that claim (death) does not resolve the underlying legal question but rather defers it. Ushabti practitioners who encounter assassination outcomes in Kowloon's commercial context raise questions about who held the underlying claim, whether the claim was legitimate, and what liability attaches to the claimant. This framing makes the referral chain's concealment of claim-holders specifically significant: concealing who commissioned an assassination is, in Ushabti doctrine, concealing who holds the claim, which creates a persistent unresolved legal liability that the concealment does not eliminate. Kowloon's Jade Magistracy has several Ushabti-trained clerks whose filings on assassination-adjacent cases have produced novel liability theories that the Magistracy has neither accepted nor formally rejected.
